  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Lifesaving humanitarian assistance through Rapid WASH emergency response in Borno State, Nigeria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project focuses on addressing the emergency WASH needs of 40,000 IDPs, host communities and returnees in Borno State, Nigeria as part of Oxfam&apos;s Rapid Response Team (RRT). Oxfam&apos;s RRT strategy aims to respond to live-saving WASH, EFSVL and Protection needs in newly accessible areas, areas with sudden population displacements or areas with WASH related disease outbreaks. Furthermore Oxfam&apos;s RRT aims to support other NGOs in  areas where capacity has been overwhelmed or where requests are made for additional support. Oxfam&apos;s Rapid Response Team is multi-sectoral -comprising of WASH, EFSVL and Protection Components - and all new assessments will be done by a multi-sectorial team focusing on these three sectors. Whilst this project focuses on WASH response, intervention capacity in food security, livelihoods and protection will be ensured through other funding. Gender is mainstreamed all throughout the project cycle. 
Locations are not specified for this grant as the Rapid Response Team will respond in areas that meet a specific set of triggers for a response defined in Oxfam&apos;s SOPs for its RRT, which are: 1) sudden population displacement over a certain threshold 2) Disease Outbreak 3) Malnutrition rates (GAM) above 10% 4) (OXFAM RRT and Emergency Evaluation 2017) requests to respond by both the WASH sector and the OCHA Rapid Response Mechanism. The project is not seen to duplicate the Rapid Response Mechanism (RRM) , but rather to complement it, and Oxfam actively coordinates its RRT responses within the RRM mechanism currently. Oxfam&apos;s RRT will retain capacity to respond to sudden onset crises in Borno State for a maximum of 3 months, giving additional time to stabilise access to water, sanitation and hygiene information post-RRM response and pre-other humanitarian actors entering or scaling up in each location. Thus the RRT is envisioned to be a bridging mechanism between the short term response of the RRM and the longer term response of humantarian actors with longer term funding. 
OXFAM has also committed to contribute toward preventing and respond to violence against women and girls (VAWG) and gender-based violence (GBV) in emergencies through these type of projects. This includes reducing risks across humanitarian programmes, increasing access to services for survivors, tackling the root causes of violence, and promoting women&#x2019;s rights. (Ref: OXFAM Publication on GBV, ISBN 978-1-78077-513-5)</narrative>
  </description>
